{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17233"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17233"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69499"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9923"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17233"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54951"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"7620"},{"type":"tags","id":"10748"},{"type":"tags","id":"10753"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69499"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEpigenetic modifications can be influenced by various environmental factors including diet, stress, and exposure to toxins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how environmental factors can influence gene expression?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Random insertion of new genetic material","Reversal of nucleotide base pairing","Permanent deletion of affected genes","Modification of DNA methylation patterns","Direct mutation of DNA sequences"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEnvironmental factors can influence gene expression through \u003Cstrong\u003Emodification of DNA methylation patterns\u003C/strong\u003E. These epigenetic changes can activate or silence genes without altering the DNA sequence itself. DNA methylation typically occurs at CpG sites and is influenced by factors such as diet, stress, and environmental exposures.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect mutation of DNA sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - Environmental factors can affect gene expression without mutating the DNA sequence\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermanent deletion of affected genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Epigenetic modifications do not remove genes but rather influence their expression\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom insertion of new genetic material\u003C/strong\u003E - Environmental factors do not typically add new genetic material\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversal of nucleotide base pairing\u003C/strong\u003E - Base pairing remains stable; changes occur through chemical modifications to existing DNA\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EEpigenetic modifications are potentially reversible and can be inherited across cell divisions and sometimes across generations. Common modifications include DNA methylation, histone modifications, and changes in chromatin structure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Environmental factors can modify gene expression through epigenetic mechanisms without changing DNA sequence.","DNA methylation and histone modifications are key epigenetic changes influenced by environmental exposures.","Epigenetic modifications can be inherited across generations but are potentially reversible."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Nilsson EE, Skinner MK. Environmentally Induced Epigenetic Transgenerational Inheritance of Reproductive Disease. Biol Reprod. 2015 Dec;93(6):145. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6058737/","Breton CV, Landon R, Kahn LG, Enlow MB, Peterson AK, Bastain T, et al. Exploring the evidence for epigenetic regulation of environmental influences on child health across generations. Communications Biology. 2021;4(1):769. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s42003-021-02316-6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54951"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17233"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54951"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T10:09:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T10:10:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9923"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":